    <segment id="1" parent="16" relname="preparation">
You have made an interesting point.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="span"> From what I have been able to ascertain from the readings and research, the HCI community has recognized that there are many types of users and has developed the concept of universal usability.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="concession"> Universal usability implies that an interface is usable by all user types.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="18" relname="span"> Universal usability is very difficult to accomplish.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="9" relname="span"> Microsoft Word is a good example.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="13" relname="span"> There are hundreds of features in MS Word,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="12" relname="contrast"> some users only use a few of the features</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="contrast"> and other users use many of the features.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span"> Microsoft has attempted to make Word universally usable by making it highly customizable.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> Whether or not they have achieved universal usability is another matter.</segment>
